Kubernetes Operators and the Operator Lifecycle Manager
Objectives
Describe the operator pattern and different approaches for installing and updating Kubernetes operators.

1️⃣ What is the Operator Pattern ?
In Kubernetes, we normally deploy apps using:
•	Deployment
•	StatefulSet
•	DaemonSet
•	Job
•	CronJob
These resources run containers, but they do not manage complex applications automatically.
Example complex application:
Application
   │
   ├── Database
   ├── Backend API
   └── Frontend UI
Managing this manually is difficult.
So Kubernetes uses Operators.
Operator Definition
An Operator is software that automates deployment, management, and lifecycle of complex applications in Kubernetes.
It acts like a human administrator but automated.
________________________________________
2️⃣ How Operators Work
Operators use Custom Resources (CR).
Example:
You create a resource like:
kind: Database
name: mydb
size: 10Gi
backup: daily
The Operator reads this CR and automatically creates:
StatefulSet
PersistentVolume
Services
Backup CronJob
Workflow
User creates Custom Resource (CR)
        ↓
Operator watches the CR
        ↓
Operator creates required Kubernetes resources
________________________________________
3️⃣ Components of an Operator
Every operator has two main parts.
1️⃣ Custom Resource Definition (CRD)
Defines a new Kubernetes object type.
Example:
Database
Kafka
Redis
Prometheus
2️⃣ Operator Controller
A pod running in the cluster that:
•	Watches CRs
•	Creates workloads
•	Maintains application state
________________________________________
4️⃣ Types of Operators in OpenShift
OpenShift has three types.
________________________________________
1️⃣ Cluster Operators
These manage OpenShift platform components.
Examples:
•	Authentication
•	Web Console
•	Networking
•	Monitoring
They are managed by the:
Cluster Version Operator (CVO)
CVO:
•	Installs cluster operators
•	Updates cluster operators
•	Maintains cluster health
Command
oc get clusteroperator
Example output:
NAME            AVAILABLE   PROGRESSING   DEGRADED
authentication   True        False         False
console          True        False         False
network          True        False         False
Where:
Column	Meaning
Available	Operator working
Progressing	Updating
Degraded	Problem
________________________________________
2️⃣ Add-on Operators
These add extra features to the cluster.
Examples:
•	Redis operator
•	Kafka operator
•	MongoDB operator
•	Elasticsearch operator
They are managed by:
Operator Lifecycle Manager (OLM)
OLM helps to:
•	Install operators
•	Update operators
•	Remove operators
________________________________________
3️⃣ Third-party Operators
External vendors can create operators and distribute them via:
•	YAML manifests
•	Helm charts
•	OperatorHub
•	Private catalogs
________________________________________
5️⃣ Operator Lifecycle Manager (OLM)
OLM is a system inside OpenShift that manages operators.
It handles:
Install
Update
Upgrade
Dependency management
OLM uses custom resources to manage operators.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Operator Catalogs
OLM installs operators from catalogs.
A catalog is a container image that contains operator metadata.
OpenShift provides four catalogs.
Catalog	Description
Red Hat	Official Red Hat supported operators
Certified	Certified third-party vendors
Community	Open-source operators
Marketplace	Paid commercial operators
Example:
OperatorHub
   │
   ├── Redis Operator
   ├── Kafka Operator
   ├── MongoDB Operator
   └── PostgreSQL Operator
________________________________________
7️⃣ PackageManifest
When catalogs are loaded, OLM creates resources called:
PackageManifest
This resource shows:
•	operator name
•	versions
•	descriptions
•	install channels
Command:
oc get packagemanifest
________________________________________
8️⃣ Installing Operators
Operators can be installed using:
1️⃣ Web Console
Path:
Operators → OperatorHub
Steps:
Select operator
Install
Select namespace
Choose update channel
________________________________________
2️⃣ CLI
Using Subscription resource.
Example:
apiVersion: operators.coreos.com/v1alpha1
kind: Subscription
Subscription tells OLM:
Install operator
Follow updates
Track versions
________________________________________
9️⃣ Operator Workloads
Each operator creates two types of workloads.
1️⃣ Operator Pod
Managed by OLM
Example:
mongodb-operator-controller
2️⃣ Application Workloads
Managed by the operator
Example:
mongodb-statefulset
mongodb-pods
mongodb-service
________________________________________
